			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~EreIamJH">EreIamJH</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~EreIamJH">( 180023 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65302065">		
		on Sunday April 13, 2025 @01:00AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//linux.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23663705&amp;cid=65302065">#65302065</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65302065"><p>Started with BitKeeper changing its license because someone in the community had tried to reverse engineer the protocol.  Linus tried to defend BitKeeper, but the other devs were spending their days shouting at the BitKeeper guy while searching for something freer.  Linux coding pretty much stopped.  </p><p>Then one morning Linus posted git v0.1 and instead of searching for another system the linux devs spent the next week critiquing git.  Then they started to add patches and within a couple of weeks the system was fit for casual use.  Overnight git became the VCS that every dev used at home and dozens of other VCS' companies were out of business within the year.</p><p>Good times.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65302065">
